{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Dusty Springfield song stops.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MIA
{DIALOGUE}: Let's go.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. JACKRABBIT SLIM'S – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the past six years, 50's diners have sprung up all over L.A., giving Thai restaurants a run for their money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're all basically the same.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Decor out of an "Archie" comic book, Golden Oldies constantly emanating from a bubbly Wurlitzer, saucy waitresses in bobby socks, menus with items like the Fats Domino Cheeseburger, or the Wolfman Jack Omelet, and over prices that pay for all this bullshit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But then there's JACKRABBIT SLIM'S, the big mama of 50's diners.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Either the best or the worst, depending on your point of view.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Vincent's Malibu pulls up to the restaurant.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A big sign with a neon figure of a cartoon surly cool cat jackrabbit in a red windbreaker towers over the establishment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Underneath the cartoon is the name: JACKRABBIT SLIM'S.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Underneath that is the slogan: "Next best thing to a time machine."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VINCENT
{DIALOGUE}: What the fuck is this place?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MIA
{DIALOGUE}: This is Jackrabbit Slim's.
{DIALOGUE}: An Elvis man should love it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VINCENT
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, Mia, let's go get a steak.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MIA
{DIALOGUE}: You can get a steak here, daddy-o.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't be a..
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mia draws a square with her hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dotted lines appear on the screen, forming a sqaure.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The lines disperse.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VINCENT
{DIALOGUE}: After you, kitty-cat.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. JACKRABBIT SLIM'S – NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Compared to the interior, the exterior was that of a quaint English pub.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Posters from 50's A.I.P. movies are all over the wall
{META_DATA}: ("ROCK ALL NIGHT," "HIGH SCHOOL CONFIDENTIAL," "ATTACK OF THE CRAB MONSTER," and "MACHINE GUN KELLY")
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The booths that the patrons sit in are made out of the cut up bodies of 50s cars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the middle of the restaurant in a dance floor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A big sign on the wall states, "No shoes allowed."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Some wannabe beboppers (actually Melrose-types), do the twist in their socks or barefeet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The picture windows don't look out the street, but instead, B & W movies of 50's street scenes play behind them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The WAITRESSES and WAITERS are made up as replicas of 50's icons: MARILYN MONROE, ZORRO, JAMES DEAN, DONNA REED, MARTIN and LEWIS, and THE PHILIP MORRIS MIDGET, wait on tables wearing appropriate costumes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Vincent and Mia study the menu in a booth made out of a red '59 Edsel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BUDDY HOLLY (their waiter), comes over, sporting a big button on his chest that says: "Hi I'm Buddy, pleasing you please me."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUDDY
{DIALOGUE}: Hi, I'm Buddy, what can I get'cha?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VINCENT
{DIALOGUE}: I'll have the Douglas Sirk steak.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUDDY
{DIALOGUE}: How d'ya want it, burnt to a crisp, or bloody as hell?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VINCENT
{DIALOGUE}: Bloody as hell.
{DIALOGUE}: And to drink, a vanilla coke.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUDDY
{DIALOGUE}: How 'bout you, Peggy Sue?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MIA
{DIALOGUE}: I'll have the Durwood Kirby burger – bloody – and a five-dollar shake.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUDDY
{DIALOGUE}: How d'ya want that shake, Martin and Lewis, or Amos and Andy?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MIA
{DIALOGUE}: Martin and Lewis.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VINCENT
{DIALOGUE}: Did you just order a five-dollar shake?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MIA
{DIALOGUE}: Sure did.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VINCENT
{DIALOGUE}: A shake?
{DIALOGUE}: Milk and ice cream?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MIA
{DIALOGUE}: Uh-huh.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VINCENT
